CAPE TOWN &#8211; The board of South Africa&#8217;s power utility Eskom will investigate allegations that acting chief executive Matshela Koko violated procurement rules by giving contracts to a firm where his stepdaughter was a director.Local media reported that Eskom awarded tenders worth R1 billion ($81 million) to a company where Koko&#8217;s stepdaughter was a director at a time when he had oversight of the department at the utility that gave out the contracts.&#8220;The objective of the investigation will be to ascertain whether the allegations can be corroborated and/or substantiated,&#8221; Ben Ngubane, chairman of the board, said in a statement. 